You are implementing `lib/remotion-spec-fix.ts`, a module that applies annotation-driven patches to Remotion spec markdown files. When a reviewer annotates a video frame, this module locates the matching spec file by timestamp and appends (or replaces) a structured revision block.

Dependencies
- `lib/spec-timestamp.ts` — import `parseSpecTimestampRange` to extract `{ startSeconds, endSeconds }` from `**Timestamp:**` lines in spec markdown.
- `lib/types.ts` — import `Annotation` (with `.id`, `.timestamp`, `.text`, `.analysis`) and `Section` (with `.specDir`).

Requirements
1. Export `applyRemotionSpecFixForAnnotation(projectDir, section, annotation)` returning `SpecPatch | null` where `SpecPatch = { specPath: string; note: string }`.
2. Resolve `section.specDir`: if relative, strip a leading `specs/` prefix and join under `<projectDir>/specs/<normalized>`. If absolute, use as-is.
3. Read `.md` files from the resolved spec dir, excluding `AUDIT_` prefixed files, sorted alphabetically.
4. Match annotation to spec: iterate sorted spec files, parse each for a timestamp window via `parseSpecTimestampRange`, and select the first file whose window contains `annotation.timestamp` (inclusive start, exclusive end). Fall back to the first spec file if no timestamp match.
5. Build an annotation block wrapped in `<!-- ANNOTATION_UPDATE_START: <id> -->` / `<!-- ANNOTATION_UPDATE_END: <id> -->` HTML comment markers containing: heading "## Annotation Update", the requested change text, the technical assessment, and bullet-listed suggested fixes.
6. Idempotent writes: if markers for this annotation id already exist in the file, replace the existing block; otherwise append the block after the existing content.
7. Return `{ specPath, note: annotation.text }` on success, `null` if the spec dir doesn't exist or contains no spec files.
